    "body": "@nikomatsakis I think what @carllerche is trying to say is that in C, `const*` is a strictness opt-in, while regular pointers are assumed to be sloppy. The Rust approach **appears** to be strict in both cases, when, in fact, `mut*` is just trying to communicate sloppiness.\n\nI think both @carllerche and I would prefer `const*` to communicate strictness and plain old `*T` to communicate sloppiness. There may still be some use-case for `mut*` in that scheme (if the FFI bindings know that it actually **is** safe to mutate), and that would actually be a useful thing to communicate.\n",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
