    "body": "@wycats:  `const T *` and `T *` only have to do with whether the pointer is read-only or not. It has nothing to do with whether the data is actually immutable and `T *` doesn't imply that it's actually safe to mutate it. A `T *` pointer just allows a superset of what a `const T *` pointer would. The `strerror` type signature is that way because it existed before `const` and cannot be changed for backwards compatibility reasons. It makes sense for Rust to respect the actual C type signatures, especially since that's what automatic binding generation would do - and we _should not_ be doing it by hand anyway (too error prone and not at all portable).\n",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
